(The Prosper Loan Data Exploration)¶

by (Z. Jiang)¶

Investigation Overview¶

This is a finanacial dataset related to the loan, lenders, borrowers, interest rates, monthly payments, incomes, etc. This dataset is from the Propsper Marketplace Inc., a San Francisco California based company specializing in loan at low interest rates to the borrowers. The dataset contains 113937 entries with 81 variables. The variables included the borrower's location, financial, credit records, the evaluation measurement made by the Prosper platform, and the investor side's information. In the next few sections, I will clean up the data and explore the loan data through applying univariate, bivariate, and multivariate graphs and summaries. Specifically, I explored the dataset to address the concerns listed below.

  1. What are the characteristics of the borrowers on the Prosper platform.
  2. What are the factors may help the borrowers to obtain the money.
  3. What are the factors that play critical roles in determining the borrower rate.
  4. How the Prosper platform evaluate and manage the risk for the investors.
  5. The pattern of the investors' preference in choosing the borrowers.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables. Each loan record contains the loan amount, borrower rate (interest rate), current loan status, borrower's employment status, borrower income, and borrower credit history.

The Prosper Loan Dataset variable definitions can be found here:

The data analysis below is based on my personal interests listed above, therefore I pre-selected the data accordingly, and 24 of the variables have been included.

There are some interesting insights have been revealed from this exploration.

First, I am curious about the borrowers background. Stepping into debt is a significant decision to make for a person. I want to know more about the borrowers' background information like their living locations and their financial status.

The visualization above shows far more borrowers came from California compare to other states. The top two to five states of the borrowers using Prosper are Texax, New York, Florida, and Illinois. The potential explanations for the borrower location distribution are listed below.

  • Since the Prosper platform is based in California, it is reasonable to have most borrowers using its plaform.
  • The living expense in California is also among the highest in the US.

Since most of the money went to the top five states as shown above, I focused on the top five states and further investigated the where the large amount of loan money went.

What was the loan used for?¶

The dataset also provided the purpose of the loan as below. 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans

Let's take a closer look at the top ten reasons for borrow the loan.

Removing Unusual Data and Outliers¶

Because the ProsperRating records did not exist prior to July 2009, it shows as missing data in the earlier records. Prior to 2009, the CreditGrade was used as the evaluation system by Prosper. Since we have more ProsperRating over CrediGrade records, the rows with the CrediGrade records will be excluded from this analysis. The additional rows with the conditions below will also be excluded

  • The borrower's income information is missing
  • The borrower rate is above 0.35
  • Missing employment status information
  • Credit socre lower than 400

Bivariate Analysis¶

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The regression analysis results summary

The scatter plots above showed a positive and linear relationship between BorrowerRate and EstimatedReturn. MothlyLoanPayment and LoanOriginalAmount CreditScoreRangeUpper and BorrowerRate CreditScoreRangeUpper and PorsperRating Investors and LoanOriginalAmount

The borrower rate histogram analysis

  • The Borrower Rate histogram is highly correlated with the Prosper Rating. The decreasing prosper rate (which indicates the increasing risks) is correlated with an increasing borrower rate.
  • When colored with the income range, the peaks of the borrowers with higher incomes (USD50,000-74,999 and USD100k+) clearly shift towards left, indicating a lower borrwer rate (between 0.1 and 0.2). Interestingly, the borrowers with lower incomes(USD 2.5k to 4.9k) shift towards the right side, indicateing a higher borrower rate (0.2 to 0.35). There's a peak at 0.32 for most income ranges.
  • The plot also showed most the borrowers are employed.
  • Also, owning a home did help to decrease the borrowing rate for the given dataset.

Does the Prosper Rating system favor the house owner?

  • The plot shows owning a house did help the borrowers to get a better prosper rating scale. But for the borrowers with worse prosper rating scale, owning a house didn't help much.

Heat map of Borrower rate vs. Loan amount

  • The loan amount tend to fall on 4k, 10k, 15k, 20k, and 25k these five peaks.
  • On each specific loan amount peak, the borrower rate has a wide spread.
  • Specifically, at the 4k peak, more counts is obseved at higher borrower rate range (0.25 to 0.32).
  • On 10k, 15k, 20k, and 25k loan amount peaks, the borrower rate mainly aggregate from 0.1 to 0.25.
  • At higher loan amount 20k and 25k, the borrower rate shift towards the left compare to the lower loan amount 10k and 4k.

Prosper ratings vs. Loan Amount

How the prosper rating system affect the amount of money the borrower can borrow?

  • The plot shows the borrower has higher prosper rating scales D, E, and HR (high risk) obtain less amount of loan money.
  • Unusual point explained: The average amount of the loan money for E and HR borrowers is around 4k.
  • Since the borrower with high prosper rating scale indicate a high risk, it is reasonable that these borrowers (D, E, HR) will have more difficulties to borrow larger loan amounts on the Prosper platform.

Prosper ratings vs. CreditScoreUpper

  • The plot shows the ProsperRating system is generally consistent with the CreditScoreRangeUpper system becuase higher PropsperRating scale (low risk) is associate with higher CreditScoreRangeUpper Score.

Prosper ratings vs. Debt to Income ratio

  • The plot shows the debt to income ratio raises as the prosper rating decreases.

Income range vs. Debt to Income ratio

  • The plot shows as the income range increases, the debt to income ratio decreases.

Prosper ratings vs. Borrower rate

  • The borrower rate shows a linear relationship to prosper rating. The deteorating prosper rating leads to rising borrower rate.

Prosper ratings vs. Lender yield

  • The lender yield also shows a strong correlation with prosper rating, the improving prosper rating decreases the lender yield.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • In the heat map of Borrower rate vs. Loan amount, the hottest spot showed at borrower rate 0.32 with loan amount 4k.

I performed the data wrangling operations listed below.

  • Drop the missing rows in the above columns
  • Drop the rows which borrower rate is above 0.35
  • Drop the rows which Credit score is lower than 400
  • Drop the rows which 'EmoploymentStatus' value equals to 'Not employed' and '$0'.
  • Sort out the order of the values in PropsperRating (Alpha) and IncomeRange columns

The reasons of performing the above operations to the data are listed below.

  • The ProsperRating records did not exist prior to July 2009, it shows as missing data in the earlier records. Prior to 2009, the CreditGrade was used as the evaluation system by Prosper.
  • Since we have more ProsperRating over CrediGrade records, the rows with the CrediGrade records will be excluded from this analysis.
  • Based on the previous univariate analysis results, I decided to exclude the outliers and the rows which donot contain the necessary information for this analysis.

def qrt_trans(x, inverse = False):
    """transformation helper function"""
    if not inverse:
        return x ** (1/4)
    else:
        return x ** 4

def mean_poly(x, y, bins = bin_edges, **kwargs):
    """Custom adapted line plot code."""
    # set bin edges if non or int specified
    if type(bins) == int:
        bins = np.linspace(x.min(), x.max(), bins+1)
    bin_centers = (bin_edges[1:] + bin_edges[:-1]) / 2
    
    # compute counts
    data_bins = pd.cut(x, bins, right = False,
                       include_lowest = True)
    means = y.groupby(data_bins).mean()
    
    # create plot
    plt.errorbar(x = bin_centers, y = means, **kwargs)

bin_edges = np.arange(999, loan['LoanOriginalAmount'].max()+1000, 1000)
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = loan, hue = 'ProsperRating (Alpha)', height = 5)

Debt to income ratio vs. income ranges by prosper rating system

  • There are more outliers in the lower income ranges with extremely high debt to income ratio.

Monthly loan payment vs. stated monthly income by income ranges

  • The plot shows higher income allows the borrower to afford higher monthly loan payment.

Investors vs. income ranges vs. prosper ratings

  • With in each income range, the borrower with better prosper rating receives more investors.
  • The borrower with higher income also attracts more investors.

Monthly loan payment vs. stated monthly income vs. income ranges

  • Borrower with higher income can afford higher monthly loan payment

Monthly loan payment vs. stated monthly income vs. prosper ratings

  • The plot shows higher income allows the borrower to afford higher monthly loan payment.
  • The HR borrowers' monthly income varies from low to very high.
  • Monthly loan payment USD1.2k seems a threshold. There's a significant drop of the borrowers number willing to pay more than USD1.2k a month.

Borrower rate vs. estimated effective yield vs. prosper rating

  • The plot shows at the same borrower rate (like 0.2, 0.25), the estimated yield is below zero for HR (high risk borrower) but positive for AA, A and B (low risk borrowers).
  • The plot also reflects although the higher risk scale on the prosper ratings brings higher borrower rate, but due to the increased risk, the estimated yield may get compromised as well.

Borrower rate vs. estimated loss vs. prosper rating

  • The plot shows the improving prosper rating lower the borrow rate, it reduces the estimated loss as well.

  • The improving prosper rating also brings down the estimated loss.

  • Which further explained the odd highest 4k peak (among the other 10k, 15k, 20k peaks) observed in the LoanOriginalAmount histogram plot in the first section.

Borrower rate vs. investors vs prosper rating

  • The plot also indicates the investors in general prefer to invest the borrowers with lower risk, even it means sacrifice with lower borrower rate.

Loan amount vs. investors vs prosper rating

  • The plot indicates the investor tends to invest less money to the borrowers with high risk on the prosper rating system.
  • Specifically, the HR borrower receives the least amount of loan money from the investors, with around USD4k, which is consistent with previous findings.
  • Interestingly, this plot also shows a large number of B and C borrowers receive large amount of loan (USD25k and 35k) from lots of investors.
